<section xml:id="sec_work-energy-thm" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Work-Energy Theorem</title>

      <video youtube="Mun7c6RB140"><description>Introducing the Work-Energy Theorem.</description></video>
	
	<principle xml:id="p_work-energy">
	<title>The Work-Energy Theorem</title>
	<statement>
		<p></p>
	  <p>The net work done by external forces on an object or system is equal to the change in total energy of that system: <me>W_{net,external} = \Delta E</me></p>
	</statement>
	</principle>
	
	<p>The Work-Energy Theorem is one of the most fundamental laws in physics.  In fact, it is used throughout essentially all of science.  It says something simple but profound: if you want to change the energy of a system, something external has to interact with the system.  In most of physics, the kind of interaction that can transfer energy to a system is work.</p>
	
		<assumption>
	<title>No Heat Transfer</title>
	<p></p>
	<p>The Work-Energy Theorem assumes that no heat is transferred into or out of the system of interest.<fn>If heat is transferred, you can use the First Law of Thermodynamics instead of the Work-Energy Theorem: <me>W_{net,external} + Q_{net,external} = \Delta E</me> where <m>Q_{net,external}</m> is the net heat transferred to the system.</fn></p>
	</assumption>

